AB  - Rice production is associated with water, food security, and livelihood, and it is being affected by climate change. Additionally, rice paddies can emit greenhouse gases back into the atmosphere. This study uses the Cropwat and DSSAT models to investigate the impacts of climate change on irrigation water requirements and rice yields in the Bang Pakong River Basin, Thailand. The simulation results were then used to calculate rice water productivity and farmer income. Moreover, methane emissions from rice fields were also calculated using the IPCC equations. The study uses outputs from three CMIP5 Global Climate Models (EC-Earth, MPI-ESM-MR, and HadGEM2-ES) downscaled under RCP4.5 and RCP8.5 scenarios using two Regional Climate Models (RegCM4 and RCA4). The results indicate that, when comparing the baseline period (2000-2023) with the far future (2075-99), irrigation water requirements for rice under RCP4.5 and RCP8.5 are projected to change between - 8.6 and 9.7% and 1.7-15.3%, respectively. Rice yields under RCP4.5 and RCP8.5 are expected to change between - 4.3% to -3.3% and - 11.4% to -2.0%, respectively. Farmer income under RCP4.5 and RCP8.5 are expected to change between - 12.7% to -9.0% and - 34.4% to -5.5%, respectively. Biophysical water productivity under RCP4.5 and RCP8.5 are projected to change between - 16.7 and 5.5% and - 25.0% to -10.5%, respectively. Economic water productivity under RCP4.5 and RCP8.5 are projected to change between - 25.7% to -2.9% and - 46.8-5.9%, respectively. Calculated methane emissions from rice paddies are estimated at 134 kg/ha. These results demonstrate the negative impacts of climate change on rice farming. The information obtained from this study is helpful in developing adaptation strategies to mitigate these impacts.Graphical AbstractThe graphical abstract was designed to illustrate the key concepts of this research, encompassing the following main components: research question, study area, data, models, methodology, key findings, and conclusions.The left section begins with the research question, followed by the scoped study area and location map, which is in the eastern region of Thailand. Below this, the data sources used in the analysis are presented. At the bottom of the left section, the models applied in the study, Cropwat and DSSAT models, are indicated.The middle section features a workflow diagram that visualizes the research methodology and the interconnections between different components of the study. The diagram includes.Input data (white boxes, regular font),Analytical methods (white boxes, bold font), and Analyzed parameters (green boxes).The workflow illustrates how input data were processed through the Cropwat and DSSAT models to estimate irrigation water requirements and rice yield, and how these outputs were then used to calculate water productivity and farmers' income. At the bottom of this section, the other diagram presents the estimation of methane emissions from rice paddies, highlighting how changes in water management practices can affect methane emissions.The right section presents the study's key findings and conclusions:Comparative results for irrigation water requirements, rice yield, biophysical water productivity, and economic water productivity are shown for the baseline period (2000-23) and the far future (2075-99) under two climate scenarios: RCP4.5 and RCP8.5, assuming conventional water management practices.
   Regarding methane emissions, the findings indicate that implementing alternate wetting and drying could reduce methane emissions by up to 45% compared to conventional continuous flooding methods.
