AB  - We employed the multivariate-probit model to identify the drivers of improved aquaculture practices and estimated their productivity effects through the average treatment effect on treated (ATET). The analysis relied on the nationally representative Bangladesh Integrated Household Survey 2018-19. More than half of farmers used input management (IM), water management (WM), and external threat management (ETM) practices. Only 5% adopted improved production (IP) practices. Commercial farms used improved practices more than subsistence farms. The factors influencing adoption of improved aquaculture practices were pond area, integrated farming, location, gender, vocational training, extension services, and mobile banking. Climatic vulnerabilities like drought, salinity, and cyclones influenced use differently across farm and practice types. Farmers using IM implemented WM and ETM concurrently. Improved technologies did not always increase productivity, especially on subsistence farms. We recommend promoting vocational training, extension services, and integrated farming, particularly targeting subsistence farms in vulnerable areas.
