AB  - Purpose: Understanding why Chinese farmers decide to adopt-or not adopt-low-carbon practices is crucial for steering the country's agricultural greening. This paper builds an integrated framework that brings together psychological motives, livelihood assets, and institutional settings to explain farmers' decision-making as a whole. Methodology: We combine the Sustainable Livelihood Approach (SLA) with the Theory of Planned Behavior (TPB) to form a comprehensive model. Data were collected from 742 rice growers in four provinces in China, and the model was tested with Partial Least Squares Structural Equation Modeling (PLS-SEM). Findings: Three main patterns emerge: Firstly, Livelihood capital, farmers' perception of the environment, and policy support all relate positively to both the intention to practice low-carbon agriculture and the actual behavior. Secondly, A clear "intention-behavior gap" appears, driven largely by cooperatives: while cooperative membership strongly boosts intention ((3 = 0.502, p < 0.001), it simultaneously suppresses real-world action ((3 =-0.127, p < 0.001). Thirdly, Integration into supply chains has the strongest direct impact on behavior ((3 = 0.581, p < 0.001), effectively narrowing the gap. Moreover, policy support not only raises livelihood capital ((3 = 0.444, p < 0.001) but also directly encourages implementation ((3 = 0.185, p < 0.001). Originality & value: By merging SLA and TPB, the study uncovers distinct pathways that shape intention versus actual practice, highlighting the paradoxical role of organizational contexts. The results suggest a shift in policy focus: leverage supply-chain incentives to drive concrete actions, and redesign cooperatives to move beyond fostering intention toward providing the technical and financial support needed for on-the-ground implementation.
