AB  - Grenada, a Caribbean Island, is known for its principal export crop of nutmeg. However, the nutmeg industry is highly vulnerable to the challenges of land degradation, dependence on trade, limited economies of scale for production, and climate change. These challenges are anticipated to influence the sustainability of the industry. As a result, this study proposes the use of the soil security framework to assess the sustainability of crop production within nutmeg agroecosystems. A methodology for assessing each component of soil security was developed for the study, including land capability classification, soil health analysis, assessing crop productivity, identifying climate-smart agriculture, and revising the legislative environment. The research design and methodology incorporate quantitative and qualitative data jointly from soil resources and human participants. This approach expands existing studies by utilizing an interdisciplinary analytical approach for assessing soil security that can be implemented in the Caribbean. Through the soil security approach, the health and capability of the soil are suitable for nutmeg cultivation. Still, productivity is influenced by the adoption of management practices by farmers. These management practices are influenced by policies and programs implemented by governing stakeholders. Therefore, for sustainable agricultural production, a multi-stakeholder governing framework is recommended to effectively tackle challenges within the industry.
