KW  - IMPACTS
KW  - BANKING
AB  - The rural poor are increasingly subjected to risks from the impacts of climate change and globalization. As industrial-based agrarian development programmes expand, made possible by increases in agricultural investment and trade liberalization, new risks to the rural poor may be manufactured as more politically and economically powerful agrarian stakeholders adapt. In this paper, we describe this concept of manufactured risk and develop this political economy of global change adaptation in development. We reflect on the theoretical underpinnings of manufactured global change risk to explain the pathways through which it may emerge in industrial-based agrarian development programmes. We then provide an example that illustrates the usefulness of this perspective. We present the case of the Arenal-Tempisque Irrigation Project in Guanacaste Province, Costa Rica, to demonstrate how the adaptations of some agrarian stakeholders manufactured new risks for others. We show that these new risks ultimately prevented the industrial-based agrarian development programme from meeting its goals of increased living standards for the rural poor and equitably distributed resources, benefits, and risks among agrarian stakeholders.
