AB  - Climate change constitutes a serious threat to pastoral resources, leading to degradation of grazing lands and significant repercussions on pastoral populations whose livelihoods depend on the environment. This study aims to identify the different adaptation strategies employed by herders in response to climate change and analyze their impact on the pastoral component within the studied livestock systems. To achieve this, semi-structured interviews and focus group were conducted with 28 herders, providing detailed information on their management practices and adaptation strategies. The study also included an analysis of land use from 1985 to 2020 to understand the dynamics of change in grazing lands. Additionally, a modeling of the evolution of natural resources from 2020 to 2030 was proposed, offering a prospective approach on the future of pastoral resources at the communal level. The results revealed that herders are shifting towards sedentary farming in response to recurrent droughts, leading to the divergence of the traditional pastoral system into three distinct livestock systems: sedentary, occasional transhumant, and permanent transhumant. The land use analysis showed that these changes in livestock practices have altered the use of grazing lands. The development of infrastructure and transportation has facilitated access of transhumant herders to distant grazing areas, covering up to 75% of the sheep nutritional needs with pastoral vegetation. Conversely, sedentary herders practice year-round feed supplementation, primarily composed of maize, barley, wheat bran, and beet pulp, with a significant contribution of forages to meet sheep needs (50 to 90% of requirements). The sedentarization and reduction of water points in high-altitude pastures contribute to an increasing overexploitation of nearby grazing areas. The forecast analysis of natural resource evolution from 2020 to 2030 shows irreversible damage to these pastures under current conditions and practices, highlighting the need for in-depth reflection on sustainable solutions to preserve these resources.
