AB  - We examine whether confidence in local governments reduces the intensity of drought-induced migration. Since confidence in government stems from the assurance of support, it may reduce households' need to migrate for sustainable livelihoods in the face of drought. However, confidence may also be encouraging for migration, particularly for aspirant households, once assurance for subsistence needs is given by the local government. We investigate this puzzling relationship between confidence in local government and migration combining Round I (2004-05) and Round II (2011-12) household surveys of the Indian Human Development Survey with drought information constructed from 30 years of weather data obtained from the Indian Meteorological Department for our empirical analysis. By employing a dose-response model, we find that even though drought causes significant out-migration among farm households, the intensity of migration is lower among households having higher confidence in local government. Policy implications of our results are also discussed.
